<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-04-08T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-04-08T09:00:00-05:00" n="887" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d887">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">760g.61/62: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>)
                                <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-04-08T17:00:00+03:00"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                        1921—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 9:04
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>129. A Moscow radio dated April 6th announces the occupation of Erivan by
                            the Soviet forces. This apparently means the overthrow of the Vratzian
                            anti-Bolshevik Government in Armenia which had regained Erivan at the
                            time of the Bolshevik attack on Georgia. See my 64, February 24 [<hi rend="italic">21</hi>].<note n="48" xml:id="d887fn48">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>